hyysguyang wrote:
&gt; 
&gt; 
&gt; Hello,
&gt; Here is my practice about TDD in my daily life , But I dont know if
&gt; I make any mistakes, so could you please tell me how to practice TDD
&gt; in your daily work?Any suggestions or recommendations will be most
&gt; appreciated.
&gt; Below is one real world practice in my TDD practice:
&gt; Requirement: Reverse the setence &#39;TDD is a software devolopment
&gt; technology&#39; to &#39;technology devolopment software a is TDD&#39;.
&gt; Attention please, this is all requirement.
&gt; 
&gt; I started my coding by following below instruction:
&gt; 1. Quickly add a test.
&gt; 2. Run all tests and see the new one fail.
&gt; 3. Make a little change.
&gt; 4. Run all tests and see them all succeed.
&gt; 5. Refactor to remove duplication.
&gt; 
&gt; First step I write a test case to describe the requirement.
&gt; 
&gt; package org.opensource.test;
&gt; import org.junit.Assert;
&gt; import org.junit.Test;
&gt; public class StringReverseTest {
&gt; @Test
&gt; public void testReverse(){
&gt; StringReverser sr=new StringReverser();
&gt; String str = &quot;Tdd is a software devolopment technology&quot;;
&gt; Assert.assertEquals(&quot;technology devolopment software a is
&gt; Tdd&quot;,sr.reverse(str));
&gt; }
&gt; }

What if you started with a simpler test?

@Test public void emptyString() {
     Assert.assertEquals(&quot;&quot;, reverse(&quot;&quot;));
}

The next test would be a one-word sentence, then a three-word sentence. 
This approach might help you avoid thinking about multiple details at once.
